    "gallery_carousel": {
      "type": "gallery-carousel",
      "blocks": {
        "image-1": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-about-materials-gold.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "14k Yellow Gold",
            "text": "<p>58.3% pure gold alloyed with copper and silver. Harder than 18k, so delicate organic tendrils survive daily wear. The alloy flows better when molten, filling the finest sculptural details. A warm buttery tone that looks like it grew rather than was manufactured.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-2": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-about-materials-pearls.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "Freshwater Pearls",
            "text": "<p>Solid nacre all the way through. Thousands of microscopic aragonite layers create luster through the same physics that makes the sky blue. No two pearls reflect light identically. We choose baroque shapes because they belong in nature, not a display case.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-3": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-about-materials-enamel.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "Hand-Painted Enamel",
            "text": "<p>Applied by hand on sterling silver — the most reflective metal, which makes every color more vivid. Each polka dot, each stripe, each marble swirl is individually filled. The result: no two rings are twins, only sisters.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-4": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Screen_Shot_2026-03-25_at_10.51.27_PM.png",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "Sterling Silver",
            "text": "<p>92.5% pure silver — the most reflective metal on earth. When enamel is applied over silver, colors appear more vivid than over any other surface. The silver acts as a mirror behind the glass, amplifying every hue.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-5": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-about-stone-moonstone.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "Moonstone",
            "text": "<p>That floating blue glow comes from microscopic layers formed when ancient magma cooled. Two feldspar species separated at the molecular level, scattering light the same way the sky turns blue. We cut every moonstone as a cabochon to focus the glow.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-6": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-about-stone-aquamarine.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "Aquamarine",
            "text": "<p>Latin for \"water of the sea.\" Iron traces in beryl crystal create the blue-green. We cut ours as cabochons — where faceted aquamarine looks like ice, a cabochon looks like the sea. A deep, still pool of color that glows from within.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-7": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-about-stone-tourmaline.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "African Tourmaline",
            "text": "<p>From artisanal mines in Mozambique and Tanzania. Its crystal structure incorporates nearly every element — more colors than any other gemstone. We choose African sources for the extraordinary saturation and the traceable supply chain.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
